WEBVTT

00:27.120 --> 00:29.300
CHAPTER III

00:30.880 --> 00:38.240
One afternoon, a month later, Dorian Gray was reclining in a luxurious arm-chair in

00:38.240 --> 00:44.620
the little library of Lord Henry's house in Curzon Street. It was, in its way, a very

00:44.620 --> 00:50.440
charming room, with its high-paneled wainscotting of olive-stained oak, its creamed-coloured

00:50.440 --> 00:57.020
frieze and ceiling of raised plaster-work, and its brick-dust-felt carpet-strewn with

00:57.020 --> 01:04.860
long-fringed silk-Persian rugs. On a tiny satin-wood table stood a statuette of Clodian,

01:05.420 --> 01:12.800
and beside it lay a copy of Les Cent Nouveaux, bound for Margaret au Voila by Clovis Eve,

01:13.360 --> 01:19.620
and powdered with the gilt daisies that the Queen had selected for her device. Some large

01:19.620 --> 01:25.760
blue china jars, filled with parrot tulips, were ranged on the mantel-shelf, and through

01:25.760 --> 01:30.940
the small leaded panes of the window streamed the apricot-coloured light of a summer's day

01:30.940 --> 01:38.380
in London. Lord Henry had not come in yet. He was always late on principle, his principle

01:38.380 --> 01:41.240
being that punctuality is the thief of time.

01:42.360 --> 01:48.480
So the lad was looking rather sulky, as with listless fingers he turned over the pages

01:48.480 --> 01:54.760
of an elaborately illustrated edition of Manon Lescaut that he had found in one of the book

01:54.760 --> 02:01.740
cases. The formal monotonous ticking of the Louis Quatorze clock annoyed him. Once or

02:01.740 --> 02:07.480
twice he thought of going away. At last he heard a light step outside, and the door opened.

02:08.060 --> 02:10.920
"'How late you are, Harry!' he murmured.

02:11.540 --> 02:17.360
"'I am afraid it is not Harry, Mr. Grey,' said a woman's voice. He glanced quickly

02:17.360 --> 02:18.920
around and rose to his feet.

02:19.500 --> 02:26.560
"'I beg your pardon, I thought. You thought it was my husband. It is only his wife. You

02:26.560 --> 02:32.420
must let me introduce myself. I know you quite well by your photographs. I think my husband

02:32.420 --> 02:34.740
has got twenty-seven of them.'

02:34.740 --> 02:38.360
"'Not twenty-seven, Lady Henry?'

02:38.360 --> 02:40.660
"'Well, twenty-six, then.'

02:40.660 --> 02:46.580
"'And I saw you with him the other night at the opera. She laughed nervously as she spoke,

02:46.580 --> 02:52.360
and watched in with her vague forget-me-not eyes. She was a curious woman, whose dresses

02:52.360 --> 02:58.360
always looked as if they had been designed in a rage and put on in a tempest. She was

02:58.360 --> 03:04.240
always in love with somebody, and, as her passion was never returned, she had kept all

03:04.240 --> 03:10.320
her illusions. She tried to look picturesque, but only succeeded in being untidy. Her name

03:10.320 --> 03:15.080
was Victoria, and she had a perfect mania for going to church.'

03:15.080 --> 03:19.620
"'That was at Lohengrin, Lady Henry, I think?'

03:19.620 --> 03:27.160
"'Yes. It was at dear Lohengrin. I like Wagner's music much better than any other music. It

03:27.160 --> 03:32.980
is so loud that one can talk the whole time, without people hearing what one says. That

03:32.980 --> 03:36.900
is a great advantage. Don't you think so, Mr. Gray?'

03:36.900 --> 03:42.340
The same nervous staccato laugh broke from her thin lips, and her fingers began to play

03:42.340 --> 03:47.060
with a long paper knife. Dorian smiled, and shook his head.

03:47.580 --> 03:52.980
"'I'm afraid I don't think so, Lady Henry. I never talk during music, at least during

03:52.980 --> 03:57.620
good music. If one hears bad music, it is one's duty to drown it by conversation.'

03:59.920 --> 04:04.140
"'Ah, that is one of Harry's views, isn't it, Mr. Gray?'

04:04.840 --> 04:09.680
"'But you must not think I don't like good music. I adore it. But I am afraid of it.

04:09.680 --> 04:16.960
It makes me too romantic. I have simply worshipped pianists. Two at a time, sometimes. I don't

04:16.960 --> 04:21.420
know what it is about them. Perhaps it is that they are foreigners. They all are, aren't

04:21.420 --> 04:25.500
they? Even those that are born in England become foreigners after a time, don't they?

04:25.940 --> 04:31.580
It is so clever of them. It is such a compliment to art. Makes it quite cosmopolitan, doesn't

04:31.580 --> 04:36.940
it? You've never been to any of my parties, have you, Mr. Gray? You must come. I can't

04:36.940 --> 04:42.120
afford orchids, but I spend no expense in foreigners. They make one's rooms look so

04:42.120 --> 04:48.360
picturesque. Ah, but here is Harry. Harry, I came in to look for you, to ask you something.

04:48.740 --> 04:54.540
I forget what it was. And I found Mr. Gray here. But we've had such a pleasant chat about

04:54.540 --> 04:56.580
music. We have quite the same views.'

04:57.660 --> 05:04.120
"'No. Oh, I think our views are quite different. But he has been most pleasant. I am so glad

05:04.120 --> 05:05.560
I've seen him.'

05:05.560 --> 05:11.580
"'I am charmed, my love, quite charmed,' said Lord Henry, elevating his dark crescent-shaped

05:11.580 --> 05:15.440
eyebrows, and looking at them both with an amused smile.

05:15.960 --> 05:21.760
"'So sorry I am late, Dorian. I went to look after a piece of old briquette in Wardour

05:21.760 --> 05:26.280
Street, and had to bargain for hours for it. Nowadays people know the price of everything

05:26.280 --> 05:28.160
and the value of nothing.'

05:30.560 --> 05:36.060
"'I am afraid I must be going,' exclaimed Lady Henry, after an awkward silence, with

05:36.060 --> 05:43.140
her silly sudden laugh. "'I have promised to drive with the Duchess. Good-bye, Mr. Gray.'

05:43.140 --> 05:49.360
"'Good-bye, Harry. You are dining out, I suppose. So am I. Perhaps I shall see you at Lady Thornberry's.'

05:49.360 --> 05:54.700
"'I dare say, my dear,' said Lord Henry, shutting the door behind her as she flitted out of

05:54.700 --> 05:59.320
the room, looking like a bird of paradise that had been out in the rain, and leaving

05:59.320 --> 06:05.200
a faint odour of patchouli behind her. Then he shook hands with Dorian Gray, lit a cigarette,

06:05.380 --> 06:07.440
and flung himself down on the sofa.

06:08.240 --> 06:13.780
"'Never marry a woman with straw-coloured hair, Dorian,' he said, after a few puffs.

06:14.660 --> 06:15.780
"'Why, Harry?'

06:15.780 --> 06:22.420
"'Because they are so sentimental. But I like sentimental people. Never marry at all,

06:22.420 --> 06:29.980
Dorian. Men marry because they are tired, women because they are curious. Both are disappointed.'

06:30.560 --> 06:37.160
"'I don't think I am likely to marry, Harry. I am too much in love,' said one of your

06:37.160 --> 06:37.900
referisms.

06:38.360 --> 06:42.700
"'I am putting it into practice, as I do everything you say.'

06:42.700 --> 06:47.720
"'Whom are you in love with?' said Lord Henry, looking at him with a curious smile.

06:48.560 --> 06:52.140
"'With an actress,' said Dorian Gray, blushing.

06:53.340 --> 06:59.900
"'Lord Henry shrugged his shoulders. That is a rather commonplace debut,' he murmured.

07:00.380 --> 07:04.980
"'You would not say so if you saw her, Harry. Who is she?'

07:04.980 --> 07:13.340
"'Her name is Sybil Vane. Never heard of her. No one has. People will, some day, however.

07:13.380 --> 07:16.000
She is a genius.'

07:16.540 --> 07:24.920
"'My dear boy, no woman is a genius. Women are a decorative sex. They never have anything

07:24.920 --> 07:31.200
to say, but they say it charmingly. They represent the triumph of matter over mind, just as men

07:31.200 --> 07:36.900
represent the triumph of mind over morals. There are only two kinds of women—the plain

07:36.900 --> 07:42.720
and the coloured. The plain women are very useful. If you want to gain a reputation for

07:43.220 --> 07:49.140
respectability, you have merely to take them down to supper. The other women are very charming.

07:49.420 --> 07:56.140
They commit one mistake, however. They paint in order to try to look young. Our grandmothers

07:56.140 --> 08:03.860
paint it in order to try to talk brilliantly. Rouge and Esprit used to go together. That

08:03.860 --> 08:08.900
has all gone out now. As long as a woman can look ten years younger than her own daughter,

08:09.440 --> 08:15.320
she is perfectly satisfied. As for conversation, there are only five women in London worth

08:15.320 --> 08:21.420
talking to, and two of these can't be admitted into decent society. However, tell me about

08:21.420 --> 08:24.400
your genius. How long have you known her?'

08:24.400 --> 08:26.180
"'About three weeks.'

08:26.180 --> 08:32.120
"'Not so much. About two weeks and two days. How did you come across her?'

08:32.120 --> 08:38.560
"'I will tell you, Harry, but you mustn't be unsympathetic about it. After all, it never

08:38.560 --> 08:43.600
would have happened if I had not met you. You filled me with a wild desire to know everything

08:43.600 --> 08:50.560
about life. For days after I met you, something seemed to throb in my veins. As I lounged

08:50.560 --> 08:55.620
in the park or strolled down Piccadilly, I used to look at every one who passed me and

08:55.620 --> 09:00.740
wonder with a mad curiosity what sort of lives they led. Some of them fascinated me, others

09:00.740 --> 09:07.640
filled me with terror. There was exquisite poison in the air. I had a passion for sensations.'

09:08.560 --> 09:16.020
"'One evening, about seven o'clock, I determined to go out in search of some adventure. I felt

09:16.020 --> 09:22.240
that this grey, monstrous London of ours, with its myriads of people, its splendid sinners,

09:22.280 --> 09:28.220
and its sordid sins, as you once said, must have something in store for me. I fancied

09:28.220 --> 09:35.400
a thousand things. The mere danger gave me a sense of delight. I remember what you had

09:35.400 --> 09:39.160
said to me on that wonderful night when we first dined together about the search for

09:39.160 --> 09:44.680
beauty being the poisonous secret of life. I don't know what I expected, but I went out

09:44.680 --> 09:50.440
and wandered eastward, soon losing my way in a labyrinth of grimy streets and black

09:50.440 --> 09:57.480
grassless squares. About half past eight I passed by a little third-rate theatre with

09:57.480 --> 10:04.140
a great flaring gas-jets and gaudy playbills, a hideous Jew in the most amazing waistcoat

10:04.140 --> 10:10.420
I have ever beheld in my life was standing at the entrance, smoking a vile cigar. He

10:10.420 --> 10:15.800
had greasy ringlets and an enormous diamond blazed in the centre of a soiled shirt.

10:16.720 --> 10:23.260
"'Have a box, my lord,' he said when he saw me, and he took off his hat with an act of

10:23.260 --> 10:29.820
gorgeous civility. There was something about him, Harry, that amused me. He was such a

10:29.820 --> 10:35.340
gentleman. You will laugh at me, I know, but I really went in and paid a whole guinea for

10:35.340 --> 10:42.700
a stage-box. To the present day I can't make out why I did so, and yet if I hadn't, my

10:42.700 --> 10:48.800
dear Harry, if I hadn't I would have missed the greatest romance of my life. I see you

10:48.800 --> 10:55.320
are laughing, it is horrid of you. I am not laughing, Dorian, at least I am not laughing

10:55.320 --> 11:02.880
at you. But you should not say the greatest romance of your life. You should say the first

11:02.880 --> 11:09.620
romance of your life. You will always be loved, and you will always be in love with love.

11:10.500 --> 11:14.760
There are exquisite things in store for you. This is merely the beginning.'

11:15.600 --> 11:20.320
"'Do you think my nature so shallow?' cried Dorian Gray angrily.

11:20.320 --> 11:24.060
"'No, I think your nature so deep.'

11:24.820 --> 11:26.040
"'How do you mean?'

11:26.840 --> 11:34.940
"'My dear boy, people only love once in their lives are really shallow people. What they call

11:34.940 --> 11:42.480
their loyalty and their fidelity, I call either the lethargy of custom or the lack of imagination.

11:43.500 --> 11:50.140
Faithlessness is to the emotional life what consistency is to the intellectual life.

11:50.760 --> 11:56.820
Simply a confession of failure. But I don't want to interrupt you. Go on with your story.'

11:58.460 --> 12:05.240
"'Well, I found myself seated in a horrid little private box with a vulgar drop scene staring me

12:05.240 --> 12:11.180
in the face. I looked out behind the curtain and surveyed the house. It was a tawdry affair, all

12:11.180 --> 12:18.700
cupids and cornucopias like a third-rate wedding cake. The gallery and pit were fairly full,

12:19.280 --> 12:25.160
but the two rows of dingy stalls were quite empty, and there was hardly a person in what I

12:25.160 --> 12:31.860
supposed they called the dress circle. Women went about with oranges and ginger beer,

12:31.860 --> 12:37.100
and there was a terrible consumption of nuts going on. It must have been just like the palmy

12:37.100 --> 12:44.320
days of British drama. Just like, I should fancy, and very horrid. I began to wonder what on earth

12:44.320 --> 12:49.480
I should do when I caught sight of the playbill. What do you think the play was, Harry?'

12:49.480 --> 12:58.100
"'I should think, oh, the idiot boy, or dumb but innocent. Our fathers used to like that sort of

12:58.100 --> 13:04.080
piece, I believe. The longer I live, Dorian, the more keenly I feel that whatever was good

13:04.080 --> 13:12.120
for our fathers is not good enough for us. In art, as in politics, les grands prêts ont toujours trop.'

13:14.100 --> 13:22.060
"'This play was good enough for us, Harry. It was Romeo and Juliet. I must admit I was rather

13:22.060 --> 13:27.140
annoyed at the idea of seeing Shakespeare done in such a wretched whole of a place. Still,

13:27.140 --> 13:33.420
I felt interested in a sort of way. At any rate, I determined to wait for the first act.

13:33.580 --> 13:38.680
There was a dreadful orchestra, presided over by a young Jew who sat to the cracked piano that

13:38.680 --> 13:45.820
nearly drove me away. But at last the drop scene was drawn up and the play began. Romeo was a stout

13:45.820 --> 13:52.240
elderly gentleman with corked eyebrows, a husky tragedy voice, and a figure like a beer-barrel.

13:53.240 --> 13:59.320
Recuscio was almost as bad. He was played by the low comedian who would introduce gags of his own

13:59.320 --> 14:05.240
and went on most familiar terms with the pit. They were as grotesque as the scenery, and that

14:05.240 --> 14:14.720
looked as if it had come out of a pantomime of fifty years ago. But Juliet? Harry, imagine a girl

14:14.720 --> 14:21.120
hardly seventeen years of age, with a little flower-like face, a small Greek head with plaited

14:21.120 --> 14:28.940
coils of dark brown hair, eyes that were violet wells of passion, lips that were like the petals

14:28.940 --> 14:35.520
of a rose. She was the loveliest thing I'd ever seen in my life. You said to me once that

14:35.520 --> 14:42.140
pathos left you unmoved, but that beauty, mere beauty, could fill your eyes with tears? I tell

14:42.140 --> 14:47.840
you, Harry, I could hardly see this girl for the mist of tears that came across me. And her voice?

14:47.960 --> 14:54.580
Oh, I never heard such a voice. It was very low at first, with deep mellow notes that seemed to

14:54.580 --> 15:01.340
singly fall upon one's ear. Then it became a little louder and sounded like a flute or a

15:01.340 --> 15:07.340
distant hat-bois. In the garden scene it had all the tremulous ecstasy that one hears just before

15:07.340 --> 15:13.060
dawn when nightingales are singing. There were moments later on when it had the wild passion

15:13.060 --> 15:19.060
of violins. You know how a voice can stir one. Your voice and the voice of Sybil Vane are two

15:19.060 --> 15:24.640
that I shall never forget. When I close my eyes, I hear them, and each one of them is saying

15:24.640 --> 15:31.860
something different. I don't know which to follow. Why should I not love her? Harry, I do love her.

15:32.300 --> 15:37.660
She is everything to me in life. Night after night I go to see her play. One evening she is

15:37.660 --> 15:43.740
Rosalind, the next she is Imogen. I have seen her die in the gloom of an Italian tomb, sucking the

15:43.740 --> 15:49.060
poison from her lover's lips. I have watched her wandering through the forest of Arden, disguised

15:49.060 --> 15:54.860
as a pretty boy in hose and doublet and dainty cap. She has been mad, and has come into the presence

15:54.860 --> 16:01.240
of a guilty king, and has given him rue to wear, with bitter herbs to taste of. She has been

16:01.240 --> 16:07.820
innocent, and the black hands of jealousy has crushed her reed-like throat. I have seen her in

16:07.820 --> 16:14.120
every age and in every costume. Ordinary women never appeal to one's imagination. They are limited

16:14.120 --> 16:21.960
to their century. No glamour ever transfigures them. One knows their minds as easily as one knows

16:21.960 --> 16:29.640
their bonnets. One can always find them. There is no mystery in one of them. They ride in the park,

16:29.820 --> 16:35.360
in the morning, and chatter at tea parties in the afternoon. They have the stereotyped smile in their

16:35.360 --> 16:43.540
fashionable manner. They are quite obvious. But an actress? How different an actress is. Why didn't

16:43.540 --> 16:49.640
you tell me that the only thing worth loving is an actress? Because I have loved so many of them,

16:49.820 --> 16:58.580
Dorian. Oh, yes, horrid people with dyed hair and painted faces. Don't run down dyed hair and painted

16:58.580 --> 17:05.640
faces. There is an extraordinary charm in them sometimes. I wish now I had not told you about

17:05.640 --> 17:13.780
Sibyl Vane. You could not have helped telling me, Dorian. All through your life you will tell me

17:13.780 --> 17:21.800
everything you do. Yes, Harry, I believe that is true. I cannot help telling you things.

17:21.800 --> 17:26.320
You have a curious influence over me. If I ever did a crime,

17:27.240 --> 17:30.440
I would come and confide it to you. You would understand me.

17:32.140 --> 17:38.980
People like you, the willful sunbeams of life, don't commit crimes, Dorian. But I am much obliged

17:38.980 --> 17:44.640
for the compliment all the same. And now, tell me. Reach me the matches, like a good boy.

17:44.640 --> 17:51.080
Thanks. Tell me. Where are your relations with Sibyl Vane?

17:51.960 --> 17:56.800
Dorian Gray leaped to his feet with flushed cheeks and burning eyes.

17:57.240 --> 18:00.220
Harry, Sibyl Vane is sacred.

18:01.240 --> 18:05.940
It is only the sacred things that are worth touching, Dorian, said Lord Henry,

18:06.480 --> 18:13.160
with a strange touch of pathos in his voice. But why should you be annoyed? I suppose she will

18:13.160 --> 18:18.040
be yours some day. When one isn't love, one always begins by deceiving oneself,

18:18.160 --> 18:23.820
and one always ends by deceiving others. That is what the world calls romance.

18:24.760 --> 18:31.500
But you know her, at any rate, I suppose? Of course I know her. On the first night I was

18:31.500 --> 18:35.780
at the theatre, the horrid old Jew came round to the box after the performance was over,

18:36.180 --> 18:40.820
and offered to bring me behind the scenes and introduce me to her. I was furious with him,

18:40.820 --> 18:46.060
told him that Juliet had been dead for hundreds of years, and that her body was lying in a marble

18:46.060 --> 18:53.000
tomb in Verona. I think, from his blank look of amazement, that he thought I had taken too

18:53.000 --> 18:58.560
much champagne or something. I am not surprised. I was not surprised either.

18:59.620 --> 19:04.040
Then he asked me if I wrote for any of the newspapers. I told him I never even read them.

19:04.500 --> 19:09.540
He seemed terribly disappointed in that, and confided to me that all the dramatic critics

19:09.540 --> 19:15.180
were in conspiracy against him, and that they were all to be bought. I believe he was quite

19:15.180 --> 19:20.980
right there, but on the other hand most of them are not at all expensive. Well, he seemed to think

19:20.980 --> 19:25.360
they were beyond his means. By this time the lights were being put out in the theatre,

19:25.360 --> 19:31.380
and I had to go. He wanted me to try some cigars, which he strongly recommended, I declined.

19:31.820 --> 19:36.480
The next night, of course, I arrived at the theatre again. When he saw me he made a low bow

19:36.480 --> 19:42.280
and assured me that I was a patron of art. He was a most offensive brute, though he had an

19:42.280 --> 19:48.600
extraordinary passion for Shakespeare. He told me once, with an air of pride, that his three

19:48.600 --> 19:54.600
bankruptcies were due entirely to the poet whom he insisted on calling The Bard. He seemed to

19:54.600 --> 20:01.220
think it a distinction. It was a distinction, my dear Dorian, a great distinction. But when

20:01.220 --> 20:08.660
did you first speak to Mrs. Sybilvane? The third night. She had been playing Rosalind.

20:08.920 --> 20:14.360
I could not help going around. I had thrown her some flowers, and she looked at me. At least

20:14.360 --> 20:20.880
I fancied she had. The old Jew was persistent. He seemed determined to bring me behind, so I

20:20.880 --> 20:27.820
consented. It was curious my not wanting to know her, wasn't it? No, I don't think so.

20:28.480 --> 20:35.820
My dear Harry, why? I'll tell you some other time. Now I want to know about the girl. Sybil? Oh!

20:36.160 --> 20:44.140
She was so shy and so gentle. There was something of a child about her. Her eyes opened wide in

20:44.140 --> 20:49.440
exquisite wonder when I told her what I thought of her performance, and she seemed quite unconscious

20:49.440 --> 20:56.780
of her power. I think we were both rather nervous. The old Jew stood grinning at the doorway of the

20:56.780 --> 21:02.340
green room, making elaborate speeches about us both, while we stood looking at each other like

21:02.340 --> 21:09.280
children. He would insist on calling me my lord. So I had assured Sybil that I was not anything

21:09.280 --> 21:14.360
of the kind. She said quite simply to me, You look more like a prince.

21:15.480 --> 21:21.380
But my word, Dorian, Miss Sybil knows how to make compliments. You don't understand her, Harry.

21:22.020 --> 21:27.620
She regarded me merely as a person in a play. She knows nothing of life. She lives with a mother,

21:27.880 --> 21:34.400
a faded, tired woman who played Lady Capulet in a sort of magenta dressing wrapper on the first

21:34.400 --> 21:41.880
night, and looks as if she'd seen better days. I know that look. It always depresses me.

21:42.540 --> 21:46.140
The Jew wanted to tell me her history, but I said it did not interest me.

21:46.140 --> 21:51.760
You're quite right. There was always something infinitely mean about other people's tragedies.

21:52.620 --> 21:56.840
Sybil is the only thing I care about. What is it to me where she

21:56.840 --> 22:02.280
came from? From a little head to a little feet she is absolutely and entirely divine.

22:03.440 --> 22:08.540
I go to see her act every night of my life, and every night she is more marvellous.

22:09.740 --> 22:13.200
That is the reason, I suppose, that you will never dine with me now.

22:13.200 --> 22:19.940
I thought you must have some curious romance on hand. You have, but it's not quite what I expected.

22:21.260 --> 22:25.360
My dear Harry, we either lunch or sup together every day,

22:25.640 --> 22:31.800
and I've been to the opera with you several times. You always come dreadfully late. Well,

22:31.800 --> 22:38.180
I can't help going to see Sybil play, even if it is only for an act. I get hungry for her presence,

22:38.220 --> 22:42.780
and when I think of the wonderful soul that is hidden away in that little ivory body I am

22:42.780 --> 22:50.080
filled with awe. You can dine with me tonight, Dorian, can't you? He shook his head. Tonight

22:50.620 --> 22:58.980
she is Imogen, he answered. Tomorrow night she will be Juliet. When is she Sybil Vane?

23:00.120 --> 23:08.300
Never. I congratulate you. How horrid you are! She is all the great heroines of the world in one.

23:08.300 --> 23:15.860
She is more than an individual, you laugh, but I tell you she has genius. I love her,

23:16.720 --> 23:24.020
and I must make her love me. You, who know all the secrets of life, tell me how to charm

23:24.020 --> 23:30.140
Sybil Vane to love me. I want to make Romeo jealous. I want the dead lovers of the world

23:30.140 --> 23:36.880
to hear our laughter and grow sad. I want a breath of our passion to stir their dust into

23:36.880 --> 23:41.860
consciousness, to wake their ashes into pain. My God, Harry, how I worship her!

23:42.280 --> 23:48.320
He was walking up and down the room as he spoke, hectic spots of red burned on his cheeks. He was

23:48.320 --> 23:54.960
terribly excited. Lord Henry watched him with a subtle sense of pleasure. How different he was

23:54.960 --> 24:01.780
now from the shy frightened boy he had met in Basil Hallward's studio. His nature had developed

24:01.780 --> 24:08.580
like a flower, had borne blossoms of scarlet flame. Out of its secret hiding-place had crept

24:08.580 --> 24:12.560
his soul, and desire had come to meet it on the way.

24:13.620 --> 24:21.020
And what do you propose to do? said Lord Henry at last. I want you and Basil to come with me

24:21.020 --> 24:26.300
some night and see her act. I've not the slightest fear of the result. You won't be able to refuse

24:26.300 --> 24:31.760
to recognise her genius. Then we must get her out of the Jews' hands. She's bound to him for

24:31.760 --> 24:37.640
three years, at least two years and eight months for the present time. I will have to pay him

24:37.640 --> 24:43.280
something, of course. When all that is settled, I will take a West End theatre and bring her out

24:43.280 --> 24:51.140
properly. She will make the world as mad as she has made me. Impossible, dear boy. Yes, she will.

24:52.280 --> 24:58.100
She has not merely art, consummate art instinct in her, but she has personality, too.

24:58.740 --> 25:04.760
And you have often told me that it is personalities, not principles, that move the age.

25:05.820 --> 25:13.380
Well, what night shall we go? Let me see. Today's Tuesday. Let us fix tomorrow.

25:14.340 --> 25:20.260
She plays Juliet tomorrow. All right, the Bristol at eight o'clock, and I will get Basil.

25:21.160 --> 25:26.740
Not eight. Hurry, please. Half-past six. We must be there before the curtain rises. You must see

25:26.740 --> 25:34.040
her in the first act, where she meets Romeo. Half-past six? What an hour!

25:35.080 --> 25:39.160
It will be like having a meat-tea, however, just as you wish.

25:40.120 --> 25:43.400
Shall you see Basil between this and then, or shall I write to him?

25:43.600 --> 25:48.600
Dear Basil, I have not laid eyes on him for a week. It is rather horrid of me,

25:48.820 --> 25:53.440
as he has sent me my portrait in the most wonderful frame designed by himself,

25:53.440 --> 25:58.100
and though I am a little jealous of it for being a whole month younger than I am,

25:58.100 --> 26:03.760
I must admit that I delight in it. Perhaps you would better write him. I don't want

26:03.760 --> 26:07.300
to see him alone. He says things that annoy me.

26:09.160 --> 26:15.720
He gives you good advice, I suppose. People are always giving away things they need most themselves.

26:16.760 --> 26:21.180
You don't mean to say that Basil has got any passion or any romance in him?

26:21.740 --> 26:26.060
I don't know whether he has any passion, but he certainly has romance,

26:26.620 --> 26:31.660
said Lord Henry, with an amused look in his eyes. Has he never let you know that?

26:32.600 --> 26:38.760
Never. I must ask him about it. I am rather surprised to hear it. He is the

26:38.760 --> 26:42.440
best of fellows, but he seems to me to be just a bit of a philistine.

26:43.460 --> 26:46.380
Since I have known you, Harry, I have discovered that.

26:47.980 --> 26:54.040
Basil, my dear boy, puts everything that is charming in him into his work.

26:54.740 --> 26:59.620
The consequence is that he has nothing left for life but his prejudices, his principles,

26:59.640 --> 27:04.980
and his common sense. The only artists I have ever known who are personally delightful are

27:04.980 --> 27:09.960
bad artists. Good artists give everything to their art, and consequently are perfectly

27:09.960 --> 27:15.020
uninteresting in themselves. A great poet, a really great poet,

27:15.880 --> 27:22.880
is the most unpoetical of all creatures, but inferior poets are absolutely fascinating.

27:24.680 --> 27:30.220
The worse their rhymes are, the more picturesque they look. The mere fact of having published a

27:30.220 --> 27:35.620
book of second-rate sonnets makes a man quite irresistible. He lives the poetry that he cannot

27:35.620 --> 27:40.140
write. The others write the poetry that they dare not realise.

27:41.180 --> 27:46.600
I wonder, is that really so, Harry? said Dorian Gray, putting some perfume on his

27:46.600 --> 27:50.520
handkerchief out of a small gold-topped bottle that stood on the table.

27:51.220 --> 27:57.040
It must be, if you say so. And now I must be off. Imogen is waiting for me.

27:57.200 --> 28:00.180
And don't forget about tomorrow. Good-bye.

28:00.180 --> 28:06.360
As he left the room, Lord Henry's heavy eyelids drooped, and he began to think.

28:07.360 --> 28:13.740
Certainly few people had ever interested him so much as Dorian Gray, and yet the lad's mad

28:13.740 --> 28:18.940
adoration of someone else caused him not the slightest pang of annoyance or jealousy.

28:19.860 --> 28:26.260
He was pleased by it. It made him a more interesting study. He had always been enthralled

28:26.260 --> 28:31.160
by the methods of science, but the ordinary subject matter of science had seemed to him

28:31.160 --> 28:39.000
trivial and of no import. And so he had begun by vivisecting himself as he had ended by vivisecting

28:39.000 --> 28:47.380
others. Human life. That appeared to him as the one thing worth investigating.

28:48.220 --> 28:55.040
There was nothing else of any value compared to it. It was true that as one watched life in its

28:55.040 --> 29:00.920
curious crucible of pain and pleasure, one could not wear over one's face a mask of glass,

29:01.320 --> 29:06.640
or keep the sulfurous fumes from troubling the brain and making the imagination turbid with

29:07.320 --> 29:15.420
monstrous fancies and misshapen dreams. There were poisons so subtle that to know their properties

29:15.420 --> 29:20.940
one had to sicken of them. There were maladies so strange that one had to pass through them

29:20.940 --> 29:26.700
if one sought to understand their nature. And yet what a great reward one received!

29:27.400 --> 29:33.420
How wonderful the whole world became to one! To note the curious hard logic of passion

29:33.420 --> 29:37.780
and the emotional coloured life of the intellect, to observe where they met

29:37.780 --> 29:43.680
and where they separated, at one point they became one and at what point they were at discord,

29:44.200 --> 29:48.280
there was a delight in that. What matter was the cost?

29:48.800 --> 29:52.240
One could never pay too high a price for any sensation.

29:53.540 --> 30:00.380
He was conscious, and the thought brought a gleam of pleasure into his brown-ugget eyes,

30:01.160 --> 30:06.280
that it was through certain words of his, musical words said with musical utterance,

30:06.660 --> 30:12.200
that Dorian Gray's soul had turned to this white girl and bowed in worship before her.

30:12.200 --> 30:18.480
To a large extent the lad was his own creation. He had made him premature,

30:18.960 --> 30:23.800
that was something. Ordinary people waited till life disclosed to them its secret,

30:23.900 --> 30:29.720
but to the few, to the elect, the mysteries of life were revealed before the veil was

30:29.720 --> 30:35.780
drawn away. Sometimes this was the effect of art, and chiefly of the art of literature,

30:35.780 --> 30:41.380
which dealt immediately with the passions and the intellect. But now and then a complex

30:41.380 --> 30:47.160
personality took the place, and assumed the office of art was indeed, in its way,

30:47.640 --> 30:54.320
a real work of art, life having its elaborate masterpieces just as poetry has, or sculpture,

30:54.620 --> 31:01.800
or painting. Yes, the lad was premature. He was gathering his harvest while it was yet spring.

31:01.800 --> 31:07.620
The pulse and passion of youth were in him, but he was becoming self-conscious.

31:08.220 --> 31:13.460
It was delightful to watch him. With his beautiful face, and his beautiful soul,

31:13.640 --> 31:19.660
he was a thing to wonder at. It was no matter how it all ended, or was destined to end,

31:19.680 --> 31:24.920
he was like one of those gracious figures in a pageant or a play, whose joys seemed too

31:24.920 --> 31:34.620
from one, but whose sorrows stir one sense of beauty, and whose wounds are like red roses.

31:35.720 --> 31:43.460
Soul and body, body and soul, how mysterious they were! There was animalism in the soul,

31:43.640 --> 31:49.350
and the body had its moments of spirituality. The senses could refine, and the intellect could

31:49.350 --> 31:56.430
grade. Who could say where the fleshly impulse ceased, or the psychical impulse began?

31:57.770 --> 32:04.730
How shallow were the arbitrary definitions of ordinary psychologists, and yet how difficult

32:04.730 --> 32:10.810
to decide between the claims of the various schools? Was the soul a shadow seated in the

32:10.810 --> 32:16.130
house of sin, or was the body really in the soul, as Giordano Bruno thought?

32:16.130 --> 32:23.230
The separation of spirit from matter was a mystery, and the union of spirit with matter

32:23.230 --> 32:30.350
was a mystery also. He began to wonder whether we should ever make psychology so absolute a science

32:30.350 --> 32:37.530
that each little spring of life should be revealed to us. As it was, we always misunderstood ourselves,

32:37.670 --> 32:44.730
and rarely understood others. Experience was of no ethical value. It was merely the name we gave

32:44.730 --> 32:54.710
to our mistakes. Men had, as a rule, regarded it as a mode of warning, had claimed for it a certain

32:54.710 --> 33:01.490
moral efficacy in the formation of character, had praised it as something that taught us what to

33:01.490 --> 33:08.830
follow, and showed us what to avoid. But there was no motive power in experience. It was as little of

33:08.830 --> 33:15.170
an active cause as conscience itself. All that it really demonstrated was that our future would be

33:15.170 --> 33:21.230
the same as our past, and that the sin we had done once, and with loathing, we would do many times

33:21.230 --> 33:28.130
with joy. It was clear to him that the experimental method was only a method by which one could arrive

33:28.130 --> 33:34.370
at any scientific analysis of the passions, and certainly Dorian Gray was a subject made to his

33:34.370 --> 33:41.210
hand, and seemed to promise rich and fruitful results. His sudden mad love for Sybil was a

33:41.210 --> 33:47.850
psychological phenomenon of no small interest. There was no doubt that curiosity had much to do

33:47.850 --> 33:55.110
with it—curiosity and the desire for new experiences. Yet it was not a simple but rather

33:55.110 --> 34:02.690
a very complex passion. What there was in it, of the purely sensuous instinct of boyhood,

34:02.690 --> 34:08.330
had been transformed by the workings of the imagination, changed into something that seemed

34:08.330 --> 34:16.470
to the boy himself to be remote from sense, and was for that very reason all the more dangerous.

34:17.250 --> 34:24.010
It was the passions about whose origin we deceived ourselves that tyrannized most strongly over us.

34:24.830 --> 34:30.970
Our weakest motives were those of whose nature we were conscious. It often happened that,

34:30.970 --> 34:35.510
when we thought we were experimenting on others, we were really experimenting on ourselves.

34:36.510 --> 34:40.930
While Lord Henry saw dreaming of these things, a knock came to the door, and his valet entered,

34:41.330 --> 34:48.110
and reminded him it was time to dress for dinner. He got up, looked out onto the street. The sunset

34:48.110 --> 34:53.930
had smitten into scarlet gold the upper windows of the houses opposite. The panes glowed like glass

34:53.930 --> 35:01.610
of heated metal. The sky above was like a faded rose. He thought of Dorian Gray's

35:02.670 --> 35:07.150
young fiery-coloured life, and wondered how it was all going to end.

35:08.350 --> 35:13.770
When he arrived home, about half past twelve o'clock, he saw a telegram lying on the whole

35:13.770 --> 35:22.990
table. He opened it, and found it was from Dorian. It was to tell him that he was engaged to be

35:22.990 --> 35:25.170
Sibyl Vane.

